00:10:28,445 --> 00:10:29,766
and the project lead on Stacking.

250
00:10:30,527 --> 00:10:32,728
And I'm going to talk to you guys a bit about how Stacking

251
00:10:32,748 --> 00:10:34,609
started off in Amnesia Fortnight and kind of how

252
00:10:34,629 --> 00:10:36,130
we took it through production and some

253
00:10:36,150 --> 00:10:37,151
of the challenges we faced.

254
00:10:37,972 --> 00:10:40,033
When I got the opportunity to come up

255
00:10:40,073 --> 00:10:42,114
with an idea for a game for Amnesia Fortnight,

256
00:10:42,174 --> 00:10:45,777
one of my first inspirations was a German expressionistic film.

257
00:10:46,317 --> 00:10:48,658
And these were films, silent films from the 1920s.

258
00:10:49,899 --> 00:10:52,382
that were considered pretty experimental in their day.

259
00:10:52,902 --> 00:10:56,005
And one of the things that I always found really inspirational and interesting about these films

260
00:10:56,146 --> 00:10:58,208
is that they had really small budgets.

261
00:10:58,588 --> 00:11:00,890
And one of the ways that they compensated for that,

262
00:11:00,950 --> 00:11:03,633
one of the ways they made themselves interesting and stand out

263
00:11:03,733 --> 00:11:08,858
is that they designed these very unique, highly stylized stage and set designs.

264
00:11:11,001 --> 00:11:12,722
I was also really interested at the same time in a...

265
00:11:13,556 --> 00:11:15,918
coming up with a game that explored identity in some way,

266
00:11:15,958 --> 00:11:17,860
maybe the changing player character identity.

267
00:11:17,880 --> 00:11:19,882
And so I kind of, I did this little sketch at the time

268
00:11:19,902 --> 00:11:22,064
that was kind of fusing these two together about

269
00:11:22,405 --> 00:11:25,608
some crazy character that could wear living masks

270
00:11:25,668 --> 00:11:27,269
and when they put these living masks on,

271
00:11:27,730 --> 00:11:29,772
they would, the rest of the way they would interact

272
00:11:29,792 --> 00:11:30,753
with the world would change.

273
00:11:31,714 --> 00:11:33,696
But that, these things are just a little too dark

274
00:11:33,756 --> 00:11:35,858
and weird for the sort of first.

275
00:11:36,390 --> 00:11:37,550
game out of the gate for me, and I

276
00:11:37,610 --> 00:11:39,271
really wanted to do something a little more charming.

277
00:11:39,291 --> 00:11:40,751
And I wasn't sure where to go, and I

278
00:11:40,791 --> 00:11:42,852
saw my daughter playing with a stack of Russian

279
00:11:43,552 --> 00:11:46,033
nesting dolls. And I thought, well, that'd be really

280
00:11:46,073 --> 00:11:48,693
cool. Those are, they have their own style, and

281
00:11:48,713 --> 00:11:50,514
they're a little bit creepy, which is cool, but

282
00:11:50,554 --> 00:11:53,235
not too creepy. Like, German, anything German, really.

283
00:11:54,355 --> 00:11:56,516
And so I did this little sketch, and I

284
00:11:56,636 --> 00:11:57,876
was like, oh, we're gonna make this. And it

285
00:11:57,896 --> 00:12:00,197
was still let me explore themes of identity, because

286
00:12:01,822 --> 00:12:03,803
you know, what sort of worlds would these dolls live in,

287
00:12:03,823 --> 00:12:04,723
and what's a relationship like?

288
00:12:04,763 --> 00:12:06,244
What does it mean to stack inside another doll?

289
00:12:06,544 --> 00:12:06,824
I don't know.

290
00:12:08,025 --> 00:12:11,647
And from there, I decided that we'd go forward

291
00:12:11,667 --> 00:12:14,128
with Russian dolls, and I wasn't sure,

292
00:12:14,368 --> 00:12:15,228
what do these dolls do?

293
00:12:15,248 --> 00:12:17,610
I mean, there's a lot of things they could do,

294
00:12:18,270 --> 00:12:19,831
and I started thinking of ideas,

295
00:12:19,851 --> 00:12:21,031
and one of the first ideas was, well,

296
00:12:21,071 --> 00:12:23,132
maybe it's a game about gentlemen's hat combat.

297
00:12:24,593 --> 00:12:26,654
And, you know, they would fling hats at one another

298
00:12:26,674 --> 00:12:27,915
and resolve all their disputes that way.

299
00:12:29,207 --> 00:12:31,008
But it, yeah, it's clearly been done too much.

300
00:12:31,268 --> 00:12:37,673
So I, instead I thought of something more, more mainstream,

301
00:12:37,713 --> 00:12:40,816
which was what if they fought German industrialist nutcrackers,

302
00:12:41,416 --> 00:12:44,178
and these nutcrackers would arrive in the land of the Russian dolls

303
00:12:44,218 --> 00:12:47,261
and crush the poor little Russian dolls with their nutcracking jaws,

304
00:12:47,481 --> 00:12:49,162
and yeah.

305
00:12:49,202 --> 00:12:50,663
Again, I was just starting to get into a dark place.

306
00:12:52,476 --> 00:12:54,418
I also remember at the time that we really

307
00:12:54,458 --> 00:12:56,561
only had two weeks to make this game. So

308
00:12:56,901 --> 00:12:58,603
rather than go down these, these roads, I decided

309
00:12:58,623 --> 00:13:02,128
to just focus just on the act of stacking.

310
00:13:02,868 --> 00:13:04,991
Let's make the mechanic, and the idea of stacking

311
00:13:05,011 --> 00:13:07,094
in another doll or within a doll, the whole

312
00:13:07,154 --> 00:13:09,296
focus of the Amnesia Fortnite prototype.

313
00:13:10,658 --> 00:13:11,639
At the same time, I thought,

314
00:13:12,354 --> 00:13:14,076
Well, it'd be really cool to do an adventure game.

315
00:13:14,136 --> 00:13:18,921
I grew up with adventure games, and I work at the same company as Mr. Tim Schafer and Ron Gilbert,

316
00:13:18,941 --> 00:13:21,784
two of the pioneers of the adventure game genre.

317
00:13:21,804 --> 00:13:24,487
I thought I could benefit from some of their knowledge,

318
00:13:24,527 --> 00:13:27,350
and it'd be good to get to it before senility drives it from their heads.

319
00:13:28,371 --> 00:13:32,636
And it was really not a good assumption, but I thought it was going to work.

320
00:13:34,924 --> 00:13:38,566
So, we did the Amnesia Fortnite demo and it worked well.

321
00:13:39,086 --> 00:13:39,666
Tim liked it.

322
00:13:40,166 --> 00:13:40,706
We pitched it.

323
00:13:40,767 --> 00:13:42,387
We were fortunate enough to sign the game.

324
00:13:43,047 --> 00:13:46,909
And then we were like, oh, well, we have to actually make this now.

325
00:13:47,509 --> 00:13:47,989
That's tricky.

326
00:13:48,349 --> 00:13:53,471
And one of the big challenges for us in stacking was that we wanted to do an original high

327
00:13:53,511 --> 00:13:57,373
fidelity game, but we had a really small budget and we had a short time frame, like nine months.

328
00:13:57,953 --> 00:14:04,139
and a small team. And we wanted to do something in this downloadable space that let us do

329
00:14:04,200 --> 00:14:07,823
things that we otherwise couldn't do in big games. So maybe things are a little different

330
00:14:07,843 --> 00:14:12,228
visually and gameplay-wise. And a lot of that comes from the personality of the game, and

331
00:14:12,268 --> 00:14:16,692
personality is important to us. But personality is often expressed in the small details and

332
00:14:16,712 --> 00:14:20,436
the presentation of the game, and that doesn't, that takes a lot of time. So how are we going

333
00:14:20,456 --> 00:14:20,857
to do that?

334
00:14:22,777 --> 00:14:24,838
And we knew the expectations would be high, both internally,

335
00:14:24,998 --> 00:14:27,700
because we had just come off of Brutal Legend and spent a lot

336
00:14:27,720 --> 00:14:31,542
of time with so many characters and really manicuring this

337
00:14:31,642 --> 00:14:32,602
large world.

338
00:14:32,622 --> 00:14:34,603
We didn't want to give up that attention to detail.

339
00:14:34,963 --> 00:14:38,765
And the XBLA and PSN markets, the games were getting more

340
00:14:38,805 --> 00:14:40,466
elaborate on those when we pitched these.

341
00:14:40,526 --> 00:14:43,648
So we needed a way of thinking about making this game, like

342
00:14:43,688 --> 00:14:45,609
how we're going to make this game, some sort of guideline

343
00:14:46,149 --> 00:14:47,009
to keep us on track.

344
00:14:47,710 --> 00:14:49,971
And the term we used was economy of design.

345
00:14:50,091 --> 00:14:50,711
And by that,

346
00:14:52,310 --> 00:14:54,491
I simply mean that we wanted the game to

347
00:14:54,551 --> 00:14:57,853
have everything it needed to feel itself, but nothing

348
00:14:57,953 --> 00:14:58,953
else. No fat.

349
00:14:59,394 --> 00:15:00,954
And we were gonna start this production by, by,

350
00:15:01,154 --> 00:15:03,656
by starting small and growing instead of big and

351
00:15:03,696 --> 00:15:07,317
cut. And that sounds obvious, but actually just about every

352
00:15:07,357 --> 00:15:09,338
game I've worked on has done the exact opposite.

353
00:15:09,658 --> 00:15:13,780
It starts with really over-ambitious systems design, huge lists

354
00:15:13,820 --> 00:15:16,241
of assets, and they inevitably are cut as the,

355
00:15:16,341 --> 00:15:17,742
as the production goes on, but we didn't have

356
00:15:17,762 --> 00:15:18,482
that time to waste.

357
00:15:20,096 --> 00:15:23,258
And one of the ways we thought about it was, let's just relate everything we come up with,

358
00:15:23,338 --> 00:15:29,662
visually, gameplay-wise, narrative, to the core idea of just stacking. And if it doesn't

359
00:15:29,702 --> 00:15:34,425
directly relate to that, that almost physicality of stacking within the doll, then let's just

360
00:15:34,465 --> 00:15:34,965
not pursue it.

361
00:15:36,806 --> 00:15:41,009
And that doesn't mean, though, that we came up with a really tiny feature set up front

362
00:15:41,129 --> 00:15:43,931
and just never did anything and executed on it and we were all happy.

363
00:15:44,584 --> 00:15:47,586
wore money hats. It, it meant that we created

364
00:15:47,706 --> 00:15:50,268
headroom for ourselves that during the production, because we

365
00:15:50,288 --> 00:15:52,270
didn't have much of a pre-production, during the production

366
00:15:52,290 --> 00:15:54,191
we could look for creative opportunities to expand the

367
00:15:54,211 --> 00:15:55,072
game and enhance it.

368
00:15:56,793 --> 00:15:58,835
And one way that this idea of economy design

369
00:15:58,875 --> 00:16:01,116
really made sense, the obvious way, is that the

370
00:16:01,156 --> 00:16:03,598
characters. We basically had one character model for the

371
00:16:03,638 --> 00:16:04,158
entire game.

372
00:16:04,872 --> 00:16:10,714
and rather than, you know, make the characters interesting through lots of variation in the

373
00:16:10,774 --> 00:16:16,435
shape, we just challenged ourselves to do them with the textures itself. We did find,

374
00:16:16,475 --> 00:16:21,256
though, that, that characters, or the players, rather, needed to have some, another layer

375
00:16:21,276 --> 00:16:25,397
of differentiation on top of the characters, because the characters were used to solve

376
00:16:25,417 --> 00:16:27,298
all the puzzles in the game. They were the inventory.

377
00:16:27,798 --> 00:16:32,822
as well as the characters. So we did that by just adding simple accessories and a lot

378
00:16:32,842 --> 00:16:36,405
of hats and canes and monocles and, you know, those sorts of things. But they were very

379
00:16:36,445 --> 00:16:40,489
quick to make. They added a lot of new personality to the game as well and they accomplished

380
00:16:40,509 --> 00:16:42,591
that gameplay goal of recognizability.

381
00:16:43,523 --> 00:16:45,344
And the characters were really cheap to render, right?

382
00:16:45,364 --> 00:16:46,505
They weren't very many polygons.

383
00:16:46,885 --> 00:16:48,026
They had very few bones.

384
00:16:48,246 --> 00:16:49,747
And that meant that we could put a lot of them

385
00:16:49,767 --> 00:16:50,307
on screen at once.

386
00:16:50,347 --> 00:16:53,549
So a lot of our levels had about 100 to 200 dolls

387
00:16:53,629 --> 00:16:55,370
on screen at once moving around, doing their thing.

388
00:16:55,390 --> 00:16:58,112
And that let us create an actual world, which was really

389
00:16:58,152 --> 00:17:00,633
important to us, like we did in Brutal Legend, but in a

390
00:17:00,693 --> 00:17:01,834
much more economical way.

391
00:17:03,770 --> 00:17:06,673
The other issue that we ran into is that we, again,

392
00:17:06,693 --> 00:17:07,533
we love personality.

393
00:17:07,694 --> 00:17:09,335
We try and put personality into our games.

394
00:17:09,415 --> 00:17:12,457
But how do we do that animation-wise with just a few

395
00:17:12,497 --> 00:17:12,778
joints?

396
00:17:12,838 --> 00:17:16,241
And we considered adding animating textures or some

397
00:17:16,261 --> 00:17:17,582
sort of detailed facial animation.

398
00:17:17,642 --> 00:17:20,124
But I thought it would just be really a little too creepy to

399
00:17:20,184 --> 00:17:21,965
have an animating face on a doll.

400
00:17:22,466 --> 00:17:24,007
And it was an expensive choice.

401
00:17:24,047 --> 00:17:26,609
So we just tried to animate just using rigid body

402
00:17:26,649 --> 00:17:27,129
animation.

403
00:17:27,430 --> 00:17:28,731
And it was really charming.

404
00:17:28,771 --> 00:17:29,651
It actually worked pretty well.

405
00:17:30,266 --> 00:17:32,469
And my takeaway is to torture your animators.

406
00:17:33,550 --> 00:17:36,834
Because just give them really strange requests and see what

407
00:17:36,874 --> 00:17:38,176
they come up with.

408
00:17:38,196 --> 00:17:39,617
But they're really clever, right?

409
00:17:40,985 --> 00:17:45,366
They can communicate ideas and emotions in ways that are really long form to communicate

410
00:17:45,386 --> 00:17:47,787
other ways, but they do it really well with simple motion.

411
00:17:47,827 --> 00:17:51,848
And as an example, I had this little dog character in a level and he did a lot of tricks and

412
00:17:51,868 --> 00:17:54,048
did things like walk on his hind legs and back flip.

413
00:17:54,408 --> 00:17:58,529
And so I said to the animators, like, I would really like this dog to drag his ass across

414
00:17:58,569 --> 00:18:01,450
the ground on occasion because, you know, if you've ever had a dog, they occasionally

415
00:18:01,470 --> 00:18:02,990
do that and it's really funny.

416
00:18:03,641 --> 00:18:05,062
And, um, do you think you could do that?

417
00:18:05,082 --> 00:18:06,844
And they're like, the dog doesn't even have an ass to drag.

418
00:18:06,884 --> 00:18:07,865
And I was like, just give it a shot.

419
00:18:08,545 --> 00:18:09,346
Uh, it'll be great.

420
00:18:09,606 --> 00:18:10,747
And, uh, and they did.

421
00:18:10,787 --> 00:18:12,469
And it looked, it looked a little something like this.

422
00:18:12,669 --> 00:18:14,771
This little, let me drag him here.

423
00:18:18,875 --> 00:18:20,036
So, yeah, animators are good.

424
00:18:21,526 --> 00:18:23,447
But the art production really wasn't the only way

425
00:18:23,487 --> 00:18:24,647
that we used economy design.

426
00:18:24,687 --> 00:18:27,468
The gameplay itself centered on a series of adventure game

427
00:18:27,488 --> 00:18:29,148
style puzzles that we called challenges.

428
00:18:29,948 --> 00:18:30,989
And one of the things that made the challenges

429
00:18:31,009 --> 00:18:32,909
a little different in stacking than other adventure games

430
00:18:32,949 --> 00:18:34,350
is that they all had multiple solutions.

431
00:18:34,650 --> 00:18:36,130
The player only had to do one solution,

432
00:18:36,150 --> 00:18:40,191
but they could choose to do many different solutions

433
00:18:40,211 --> 00:18:41,612
for a particular challenge and get rewarded.

434
00:18:42,212 --> 00:18:43,692
And although that sounds like a ton of work,

435
00:18:44,112 --> 00:18:47,213
and it is, it's a lot less than creating unique puzzles,

436
00:18:47,273 --> 00:18:47,853
right, because.

437
00:18:48,199 --> 00:18:51,540
We were able to use the same art assets, the area of the world, a lot of the writing and

438
00:18:51,580 --> 00:18:52,720
set up some of the same dolls.

439
00:18:52,760 --> 00:18:58,922
So we got a pretty economical approach to replayability that way, as opposed to making

440
00:18:58,982 --> 00:19:00,542
so many unique challenges.

441
00:19:01,802 --> 00:19:06,944
And the other thing that was a nice byproduct of that is that it increased the accessibility

442
00:19:06,964 --> 00:19:11,265
of the game, which was a goal for us on stacking, was to make it very casual and approachable.

443
00:19:11,625 --> 00:19:12,185
And I think...

444
00:19:14,588 --> 00:19:18,675
In most adventure games, there's one solution, and if players try something differently,

445
00:19:19,156 --> 00:19:22,801
and it's logical, it just doesn't work, that's sort of a classic snafu.

446
00:19:22,882 --> 00:19:25,967
And in our case, since we had multiple solutions, odds were they were going to find one of them.

447
00:19:26,755 --> 00:19:28,976
And that, that worked out well. The last thing

448
00:19:29,016 --> 00:19:30,937
about challenges that's worth noting is that the solutions,

449
00:19:31,277 --> 00:19:33,037
because they could be done in any order or

450
00:19:33,117 --> 00:19:34,538
not at all by the player, they had to

451
00:19:34,578 --> 00:19:36,419
be designed so they had no dependency on each

452
00:19:36,479 --> 00:19:38,760
other. And the game flow itself had no dependency

453
00:19:38,840 --> 00:19:41,181
on any single solution. So all the way up

454
00:19:41,221 --> 00:19:43,021
to, well, I should say alpha, but it was

455
00:19:43,061 --> 00:19:45,402
probably like a week before submission, we were messing

456
00:19:45,422 --> 00:19:48,143
with the game play and swapping solutions in and

457
00:19:48,183 --> 00:19:49,624
out based on what we saw people trying to

458
00:19:49,664 --> 00:19:51,005
do in, in play tests. And if they were

459
00:19:51,025 --> 00:19:52,505
trying to do something that seemed logical, we

460
00:19:52,945 --> 00:19:54,827
We just made a new doll, coded a solution in,

461
00:19:54,867 --> 00:19:57,709
and then two days later or so, we had a whole new solution.

462
00:19:57,909 --> 00:19:58,310
It worked well.

463
00:20:00,492 --> 00:20:02,393
So we also ran into problems in that we

464
00:20:02,874 --> 00:20:04,115
had no budget for voice acting.

465
00:20:04,474 --> 00:20:06,535
But we had a lot of characters.

466
00:20:06,555 --> 00:20:08,495
I mean, we had a couple hundred unique characters.

467
00:20:08,535 --> 00:20:10,635
I think when I counted, there was about 28,000 lines of

468
00:20:10,675 --> 00:20:12,756
dialogue, a lot of stuff there.

469
00:20:13,096 --> 00:20:14,916
And so I knew we were going to have to put text on screen.

470
00:20:15,336 --> 00:20:18,537
But I was really uncomfortable with that because text on

471
00:20:18,577 --> 00:20:21,618
screen just didn't feel, I wanted it to be cohesive,

472
00:20:21,658 --> 00:20:23,458
thematically cohesive with the rest of the game.

473
00:20:24,118 --> 00:20:27,079
And then I remembered one of my early inspirations, German

474
00:20:27,099 --> 00:20:28,019
expressionistic film.

475
00:20:28,359 --> 00:20:28,519
So.

476
00:20:30,381 --> 00:20:31,804
I brought back the idea of silent films.

477
00:20:31,844 --> 00:20:34,149
And we did all of our storytelling with a silent

478
00:20:34,210 --> 00:20:36,555
film motif, and even complete with dialogue

