00:23:31,474 --> 00:23:35,638
So, back then, five years ago, while the rest of the world was making irresponsible real

555
00:23:35,658 --> 00:23:39,362
estate investments, I was writing the dismemberment code for Brutal Legend.

556
00:23:40,263 --> 00:23:44,147
And it turns out, this is actually not the first time I'd written dismemberment code

557
00:23:44,547 --> 00:23:45,388
for a video game.

558
00:23:45,408 --> 00:23:46,429
It was actually the second time.

559
00:23:46,809 --> 00:23:52,134
And as I was writing code, along with Drew, to dismember limbs and heads and spout blood,

560
00:23:52,755 --> 00:23:55,276
I kind of started to feel like I was done with that,

561
00:23:55,396 --> 00:23:58,336
and I was really excited to think about the next game that I worked on,

562
00:23:58,376 --> 00:24:01,297
as much as I loved Brutal Legend and I loved the team that I was building it with,

563
00:24:01,757 --> 00:24:03,838
that I wanted to do something different for my next game,

564
00:24:03,858 --> 00:24:06,819
that I wanted to explore a different set of emotions.

565
00:24:07,539 --> 00:24:09,900
But I wasn't exactly sure what that was.

566
00:24:09,960 --> 00:24:10,520
But fortunately...

567
00:24:11,240 --> 00:24:16,485
five years ago, I came to GDC and I saw an amazing talk by Tsutomu Kuono, who you probably

568
00:24:16,525 --> 00:24:21,048
better know as the creator of LocoRoco. And it was really inspiring for me to see this

569
00:24:21,109 --> 00:24:26,753
talk by a guy who is so clearly committed to making a, like, fun, positive, uplifting

570
00:24:26,793 --> 00:24:30,636
game. It's one of my all-time favorite games. And I was like, wow, I want to make

571
00:24:31,217 --> 00:24:36,419
a game like that. Except I don't want to copy him, I want to do something that's my own,

572
00:24:36,439 --> 00:24:40,521
that's original, because that's what we're about at Double Fine. So like a lot of us

573
00:24:40,561 --> 00:24:44,603
do, I started sort of with my childhood heroes. I thought back to the people that influenced

574
00:24:44,723 --> 00:24:50,025
me creatively. Bill Watterson, for example, the creator of Calvin and Hobbes, and also

575
00:24:50,065 --> 00:24:54,587
Jim Henson, the creator of The Muppets. And what struck me about both of these childhood

576
00:24:54,627 --> 00:24:59,510
heroes was how remarkably positive they were in their work, that people remember them.

577
00:25:00,130 --> 00:25:03,391
for the amazingly good-natured work that they did.

578
00:25:03,411 --> 00:25:04,752
And I was like, that's awesome.

579
00:25:04,792 --> 00:25:07,773
I would love to do a game with that same level

580
00:25:07,974 --> 00:25:09,734
of upbeat positivity.

581
00:25:10,682 --> 00:25:13,964
You know, I was also learning how to be a really terrible musician at the time,

582
00:25:14,264 --> 00:25:15,245
like remarkably bad.

583
00:25:16,126 --> 00:25:20,989
But along the way I was learning, I was reminded of how evocative music can be

584
00:25:21,049 --> 00:25:24,072
as a tool for creating emotion and expressing emotion.

585
00:25:24,472 --> 00:25:27,554
It's like there are very few things that tap into like our inner selves the way

586
00:25:27,594 --> 00:25:28,375
that music does.

587
00:25:29,056 --> 00:25:32,458
In fact, one day my girlfriend at the time, and that's actually not a photo of her,

588
00:25:33,939 --> 00:25:35,460
She came up to me and she said,

589
00:25:35,480 --> 00:25:37,801
you know, do you ever have like a happy song,

590
00:25:37,861 --> 00:25:39,762
a song that like gets stuck in your head

591
00:25:39,782 --> 00:25:41,903
and you just feel better for listening to it?

592
00:25:42,664 --> 00:25:43,584
You know, and of course I was like,

593
00:25:43,664 --> 00:25:46,406
nah baby, I'm all mad, I don't have happy songs.

594
00:25:46,966 --> 00:25:49,568
But, you know, of course, we all do.

595
00:25:49,588 --> 00:25:54,370
We all have songs that we,

596
00:25:55,191 --> 00:25:56,871
as a game developer, that's as macho as I get.

597
00:25:59,791 --> 00:26:02,112
You know, we all have songs that really move us.

598
00:26:02,412 --> 00:26:04,614
So when Tim came up to me later that year and he said,

599
00:26:04,634 --> 00:26:06,795
hey, I want to do this crazy thing called Amnesia Fortnite.

600
00:26:07,095 --> 00:26:08,176
Do you have any ideas?

601
00:26:08,696 --> 00:26:10,737
I was like, actually I do.

602
00:26:10,777 --> 00:26:13,058
I've got this idea for a game where you experience

603
00:26:13,098 --> 00:26:14,859
the joy of creating music.

604
00:26:15,179 --> 00:26:16,620
In fact, there's this game that I want to make,

605
00:26:16,640 --> 00:26:18,761
and it's going to be an interactive musical toy.

606
00:26:19,342 --> 00:26:20,542
And in this toy, you're going to create

607
00:26:20,562 --> 00:26:22,663
your own personal happy song.

608
00:26:23,144 --> 00:26:24,564
But the thing is, most people.

609
00:26:25,205 --> 00:26:26,926
they're not musicians, they need some help.

610
00:26:27,287 --> 00:26:29,028
So we're gonna introduce them to some friends

611
00:26:29,228 --> 00:26:30,990
who are musical monsters.

612
00:26:31,070 --> 00:26:32,951
And those musical monsters are gonna help them

613
00:26:33,332 --> 00:26:35,253
make their own personal happy song.

614
00:26:36,034 --> 00:26:38,876
Tim was into the idea and we started Amnesia Fortnight.

615
00:26:38,936 --> 00:26:40,398
Two weeks later, we made a prototype.

616
00:26:40,838 --> 00:26:43,140
I'm sorry, I forgot to mention that because we only had two weeks,

617
00:26:43,760 --> 00:26:46,222
it was going to be minimalistic environments, very simple.

618
00:26:46,322 --> 00:26:47,823
Music, monsters, the end.

619
00:26:48,784 --> 00:26:51,126
So we made that prototype, and it looked like this.

620
00:26:51,526 --> 00:26:55,289
An awesome little jamboree of musical monsters in a minimalist environment,

621
00:26:55,589 --> 00:26:57,590
and we called the game Happy Song.

622
00:26:57,930 --> 00:27:00,492
And we were super proud of it, but being Amnesia Fortnight,

623
00:27:00,532 --> 00:27:03,895
we forgot about it until two years later in 2009,

624
00:27:04,015 --> 00:27:05,716
when the end of Brutal Legend was in sight.

625
00:27:06,497 --> 00:27:08,938
And at that time, Tim came up to me, and he said,

626
00:27:08,978 --> 00:27:12,560
you know, hey, let's make a small game, you know,

627
00:27:12,680 --> 00:27:14,542
maybe something in addition to this big game

628
00:27:14,562 --> 00:27:16,463
that we know we're going to do called Brutal Legend.

629
00:27:17,343 --> 00:27:19,985
You know, let's pitch Happy Song as that game.

630
00:27:20,365 --> 00:27:21,786
And I was like, that's awesome.

631
00:27:21,806 --> 00:27:23,407
You know, I would love to pitch the game.

632
00:27:24,227 --> 00:27:25,668
But if we're going to pitch it, we actually

633
00:27:25,688 --> 00:27:28,330
have to pitch it, you know, to the suits, right,

634
00:27:28,370 --> 00:27:30,871
to publishers, that we're going to have to make this game,

635
00:27:30,891 --> 00:27:35,034
we're going to have to make it seem at least commercial.

636
00:27:38,057 --> 00:27:44,123
Yeah. And, and the thing is, like, publishers are, they have reasonable reasons for wanting

637
00:27:44,163 --> 00:27:48,386
commercial games, and the thing is that when we looked at the Happy Song prototype, we

638
00:27:48,426 --> 00:27:53,811
honestly felt like it wasn't commercial. That it wasn't actually going to be a viable commercial

639
00:27:53,891 --> 00:27:58,695
product. In particular, we felt like the Monster Friends were really, really awesome, but the

640
00:27:58,736 --> 00:28:04,701
musical toy was less so. It felt really honestly kind of niche, you know, even for us. So.

641
00:28:06,202 --> 00:28:11,648
So that was really the essence of our production challenge, was how could we adapt the prototype,

642
00:28:12,029 --> 00:28:17,314
sign the game, and preserve the vision, preserve this idea of a game about joy, of a game that

643
00:28:17,334 --> 00:28:19,136
makes you feel happier for having played it.

644
00:28:19,947 --> 00:28:22,811
So we actually did two adaptations of that game.

645
00:28:22,831 --> 00:28:24,893
And the first adaptation was to pitch it.

646
00:28:25,334 --> 00:28:27,256
And the second adaptation was to sign it.

647
00:28:27,716 --> 00:28:29,558
And our first opportunity to adapt the game

648
00:28:29,799 --> 00:28:31,801
was with Kinect, which as you all know,

649
00:28:31,821 --> 00:28:33,483
was announced with much fanfare at E3 in 2009.

650
00:28:35,845 --> 00:28:39,488
And when that came out, we're like, wow, this is a new platform, which is going to mean

651
00:28:39,568 --> 00:28:41,950
new opportunity, a hunger for new IPs.

652
00:28:42,270 --> 00:28:43,771
And it's obviously family-oriented.

653
00:28:43,791 --> 00:28:48,254
Microsoft is making a play for the Wii audience, and they're going to want wholesome, uplifting,

654
00:28:48,375 --> 00:28:51,857
positive, you know, pro-social entertainment for that device.

655
00:28:52,257 --> 00:28:55,280
There's going to be a demand maybe for new mechanics, because like there's no buttons

656
00:28:55,340 --> 00:28:56,521
and it tracks your skeleton.

657
00:28:56,861 --> 00:28:58,162
So maybe we could innovate there.

658
00:28:59,002 --> 00:29:00,743
And in the end, it was a great opportunity.

659
00:29:00,763 --> 00:29:03,906
But the question was, how could we adapt this game about

660
00:29:03,966 --> 00:29:06,808
musical monsters to really work on Kinect?

661
00:29:07,771 --> 00:29:13,852
So the idea that we had to adapt it was to change from a game about just musical monsters

662
00:29:13,952 --> 00:29:18,433
and the joy of making music into a game about the joy of interacting, interacting with other

663
00:29:18,473 --> 00:29:19,893
people and with monsters.

664
00:29:20,233 --> 00:29:23,914
And the game that we were going to make would be a collection of monster mini-games all

665
00:29:23,954 --> 00:29:25,714
about interactions with monsters.

666
00:29:26,115 --> 00:29:30,055
Of course, we wanted to keep what works, in particular the monster friends and a game

667
00:29:30,095 --> 00:29:31,336
that makes you feel happy.

668
00:29:31,356 --> 00:29:33,116
Those are still going to be the essence of the product.

669
00:29:33,556 --> 00:29:35,018
But we had to change some stuff as well.

670
00:29:35,038 --> 00:29:36,380
And the first thing that we wanted to change

671
00:29:36,680 --> 00:29:38,503
was the focus on character interaction.

672
00:29:38,543 --> 00:29:40,685
Where the original prototype was focused on music,

673
00:29:41,046 --> 00:29:43,469
we were going to focus on the connection between the characters

674
00:29:43,509 --> 00:29:44,030
in the world.

675
00:29:44,731 --> 00:29:47,334
And in order to do that, we're going to have multiple activities.

676
00:29:47,374 --> 00:29:48,115
We wanted to have.

677
00:29:48,963 --> 00:29:52,465
a game that where you could play dress up with the monsters,

678
00:29:52,485 --> 00:29:54,686
you could do a posing Simon Says game, you could dance.

679
00:29:55,127 --> 00:29:57,308
All of these things would be ways to interact with them.

680
00:29:57,728 --> 00:29:59,389
And these activities would be more physical

681
00:29:59,429 --> 00:30:00,970
because on Kinect, physical is fun.

682
00:30:01,010 --> 00:30:04,332
So we had to de-emphasize music and emphasize the physicality.

683
00:30:04,813 --> 00:30:06,233
And lastly, we want to take advantage

684
00:30:06,273 --> 00:30:09,836
of the magic of Kinect, that Kinect can see you and pretend

685
00:30:09,876 --> 00:30:11,677
that the monsters could also see you

686
00:30:11,977 --> 00:30:13,278
so that you could interact with them

687
00:30:13,298 --> 00:30:14,799
in a very direct, connected way.

688
00:30:15,713 --> 00:30:17,114
As part of that, we're like, well, if you're interacting

689
00:30:17,134 --> 00:30:18,574
with the monsters, how about also

690
00:30:18,694 --> 00:30:20,155
interacting with other people?

691
00:30:20,795 --> 00:30:24,197
We really love this idea of parent-child co-play, a game

692
00:30:24,217 --> 00:30:25,818
that parents and kids could play together.

693
00:30:25,838 --> 00:30:28,459
So we're going to make all of the activities two-player.

694
00:30:28,479 --> 00:30:30,520
We're going to have a fundamentally

695
00:30:30,600 --> 00:30:31,860
intergenerational focus.

696
00:30:31,900 --> 00:30:33,521
And you can play it with a friend, you can play it with a

697
00:30:33,561 --> 00:30:36,322
sibling, but really we want to focus on a

698
00:30:36,382 --> 00:30:37,783
parent and a young child.

699
00:30:38,603 --> 00:30:40,804
And lastly, that means it's going to be a real world

700
00:30:40,824 --> 00:30:44,046
interaction, but not just a synthetic interaction with the

701
00:30:44,086 --> 00:30:45,146
characters on screen.

702
00:30:46,753 --> 00:30:49,835
As part of that, we realized that our minimalistic environment

703
00:30:49,915 --> 00:30:50,855
wasn't going to work.

704
00:30:50,916 --> 00:30:52,856
In order to contextualize these activities,

705
00:30:53,277 --> 00:30:57,419
we needed an actual world, a place that these activities could happen.

706
00:30:57,439 --> 00:31:00,580
And we were really inspired by storybook illustrators

707
00:31:00,620 --> 00:31:02,381
like Eric Carle and Mary Blair.

708
00:31:02,641 --> 00:31:05,062
We love their flat, two-dimensional sensibilities.

709
00:31:05,583 --> 00:31:07,344
And so we said, well, we're going to have an environment,

710
00:31:07,384 --> 00:31:09,665
but we're going to embrace still this idea of minimalism,

711
00:31:10,145 --> 00:31:12,686
of a 2D, flat, simply constructed world.

712
00:31:13,617 --> 00:31:16,119
And the last thing we're going to do is players are going to need instruction.

713
00:31:16,499 --> 00:31:19,761
They're going to need to know what to do and how to do it, so we're going to add a narrator.

714
00:31:19,821 --> 00:31:22,283
Maybe, you know, a David Attenborough-esque character.

715
00:31:23,464 --> 00:31:26,085
He's going to provide exposition and instruction, but, you know,

716
00:31:26,406 --> 00:31:28,947
because some narrators are kind of strange-looking, he'll be disembodied

717
00:31:29,488 --> 00:31:33,130
and omniscient and, you know, not actually part of the real experience.

718
00:31:33,850 --> 00:31:35,671
So that was actually all awesome,

719
00:31:35,931 --> 00:31:37,371
and we adapted our game.

720
00:31:37,531 --> 00:31:38,691
We made a new prototype.

721
00:31:38,751 --> 00:31:39,592
It looked like this.

722
00:31:39,992 --> 00:31:41,652
And we called it Monster Party, because it

723
00:31:41,672 --> 00:31:43,753
was going to represent this idea of a collaborative

724
00:31:43,853 --> 00:31:45,013
social experience.

725
00:31:45,853 --> 00:31:47,333
And that was all super awesome.

726
00:31:47,433 --> 00:31:49,134
But then another opportunity came along,

727
00:31:49,154 --> 00:31:50,454
and that opportunity was in early 2010,

728
00:31:50,534 --> 00:31:53,575
when I read a Gamasutra article where

729
00:31:53,595 --> 00:31:54,955
we heard Warner Brothers had announced

730
00:31:54,975 --> 00:31:56,115
a brand new partnership.

731
00:31:56,155 --> 00:31:58,276
And the partnership was with Sesame Street,

732
00:31:58,336 --> 00:31:59,696
that Warner Brothers was going to become

733
00:32:00,096 --> 00:32:02,897
the exclusive publisher and distributor of all things

734
00:32:02,937 --> 00:32:03,637
Sesame Street.

735
00:32:03,657 --> 00:32:04,012
